00:51:19.080 --> 00:51:19.940
So basic facts.

00:51:22.200 --> 00:51:24.253
We talk about overall
levels of illumination.

00:51:25.370 --> 00:51:27.770
That's what's so remarkable
about the visual system.

00:51:27.770 --> 00:51:28.970
It's actually unbelievable.

00:51:28.970 --> 00:51:30.385
10 log units overall.

00:51:32.170 --> 00:51:36.360
But the reflected light varies
over much smaller range.

00:51:36.360 --> 00:51:39.775
In other words, you don't want
to look at directly at light.

00:51:40.790 --> 00:51:44.320
The reflected light
varies only about 20 fold.

00:51:46.010 --> 00:51:48.285
So now the question is,
how do we handle this?

00:51:48.285 --> 00:51:51.990
Well, it turns out
that the pupil, which

00:51:51.990 --> 00:51:55.220
does play a role
in this, can only

00:51:55.220 --> 00:51:58.240
adjust over a range of 16 to 1.

00:51:59.530 --> 00:52:02.600
So that's a long cry
from 10 log units.

00:52:02.600 --> 00:52:04.520
And so much of the
adaptation I would

00:52:04.520 --> 00:52:07.450
say, even more so the
adaptation that takes place,

00:52:07.450 --> 00:52:09.590
occurs in your photoreceptors.

00:52:11.610 --> 00:52:15.200
So here I'm saying this
again-- most light adaptation

00:52:15.200 --> 00:52:17.790
takes place in the
photoreceptors.

00:52:17.790 --> 00:52:19.310
Now, how does it take place?

00:52:19.310 --> 00:52:23.510
Well, the way it takes place is
that-- I mentioned this to you

00:52:23.510 --> 00:52:28.340
before-- the photoreceptor
molecules, like rhodopsin

00:52:28.340 --> 00:52:32.400
in the rods, comes
in two basic forms.

00:52:32.400 --> 00:52:36.590
You don't need to know
the chemistry of it,

00:52:36.590 --> 00:52:39.780
but you make two or simply
that it comes in two forms.

00:52:39.780 --> 00:52:41.780
We can call it bleached
and unbleached.

00:52:41.780 --> 00:52:44.725
Some people call
it open and closed.

00:52:44.725 --> 00:52:46.475
But let's call it
bleached and unbleached.

00:52:50.080 --> 00:52:51.335
This is very dynamic process.

00:52:51.335 --> 00:52:57.800
At any level of illumination a
certain percentage of molecules

00:52:57.800 --> 00:53:02.930
is bleached in each receptor
and a certain number

00:53:02.930 --> 00:53:04.300
is not bleached.

00:53:04.300 --> 00:53:07.250
And the brighter the
illumination, the more

00:53:07.250 --> 00:53:08.515
are bleached.

00:53:08.515 --> 00:53:13.600
It's dynamic, which I mean is
that the molecules constantly

00:53:13.600 --> 00:53:14.710
keep changing.

00:53:14.710 --> 00:53:17.936
So it's the overall
percentage of the ratios

00:53:17.936 --> 00:53:19.560
between the beached
and the unbleached.

00:53:20.840 --> 00:53:24.805
So that means that any increase
in the rate of which quanta

00:53:24.805 --> 00:53:28.256
is delivered to the eye results
in a proportional decrease

00:53:28.256 --> 00:53:31.150
in the number of pigment
molecules available to absorb

00:53:31.150 --> 00:53:33.150
those quanta because
they are bleached.

00:53:35.020 --> 00:53:41.880
Now, this arrangement happens
to be extremely clever.

00:53:41.880 --> 00:53:45.040
And this is
reflected in the fact

00:53:45.040 --> 00:53:49.990
that the retinal ganglion cells
are sensitive to local contrast

00:53:49.990 --> 00:53:50.540
differences.

00:53:50.540 --> 00:53:53.039
Remember, I told you there's a
center-surround organization.

00:53:53.039 --> 00:53:55.400
This is one of the prime
reasons we have that.

00:53:58.450 --> 00:54:01.110
The overwhelming
majority, like 95%

00:54:01.110 --> 00:54:04.650
of the cells in the retina,
the retinal ganglion cells,

00:54:04.650 --> 00:54:08.150
respond to contrast
differences, not

00:54:08.150 --> 00:54:10.395
to absolute levels
of illumination.

00:54:10.395 --> 00:54:13.310
And that's how we often
talk about contrast.

00:54:13.310 --> 00:54:16.320
And if you remember what
the contrast formula is,

00:54:16.320 --> 00:54:22.330
it's the contrast level
of the stimulus itself

00:54:22.330 --> 00:54:24.390
and the contrast level
of the background.

00:54:24.390 --> 00:54:28.700
You subtract one from the other,
divided by the sum of the two,

00:54:28.700 --> 00:54:30.250
multiplied by 100.

00:54:30.250 --> 00:54:32.510
I showed that to you before.

00:54:32.510 --> 00:54:34.580
So now here we are.

00:54:34.580 --> 00:54:36.930
If you talk about light
and dark adaptation,

00:54:36.930 --> 00:54:40.990
this is the basic outline
of the retinal connections

00:54:40.990 --> 00:54:42.280
that we have talked about.

00:54:42.280 --> 00:54:44.610
We have presented this
several times before.

00:54:44.610 --> 00:54:47.170
And then if you
are light adapted,

00:54:47.170 --> 00:54:50.910
you essentially have
non-functional rods,

00:54:50.910 --> 00:54:52.490
so I took them off here.

00:54:52.490 --> 00:54:55.360
But then when you darken
that, the opposite happens.

00:54:55.360 --> 00:54:57.005
And you have the rods active.

00:54:58.440 --> 00:55:01.230
But they all fit into
the same ganglion cells.

00:55:01.230 --> 00:55:04.280
And that's why at night, the
receptor fields are bigger.

00:55:04.280 --> 00:55:06.570
And you don't see color
at night because this

00:55:06.570 --> 00:55:07.990
is what the picture is.

00:55:07.990 --> 00:55:11.470
Now what you can do is
let's ask the question,

00:55:11.470 --> 00:55:15.350
how do the neurons, like
the cells in the retina,

00:55:15.350 --> 00:55:18.360
the retinal ganglion
cells how do they

00:55:18.360 --> 00:55:22.100
fire at different
levels of illumination?

00:55:22.100 --> 00:55:24.370
And that's quite an
interesting story

00:55:24.370 --> 00:55:25.890
and a very straightforward one.

00:55:25.890 --> 00:55:29.230
Here we have a cell
that had been adapted

00:55:29.230 --> 00:55:33.990
to these different levels
of background illumination.

00:55:36.290 --> 00:55:39.760
At minus 5, your
rods are functional.

00:55:39.760 --> 00:55:43.230
And what is
important to see here

00:55:43.230 --> 00:55:46.140
is that as you change quite
dramatically the background

00:55:46.140 --> 00:55:50.280
level, the eye adapts.

00:55:50.280 --> 00:55:53.140
And I should say that it's the
photoreceptors predominately

00:55:53.140 --> 00:55:54.170
that do so.

00:55:54.170 --> 00:55:56.850
And what they look at
are local differences.

00:55:56.850 --> 00:56:01.360
And so each of these
then sees a fresh,

00:56:01.360 --> 00:56:06.590
the contrast that is
created, rather than looking

00:56:06.590 --> 00:56:08.400
at absolute illumination levels.

00:56:08.400 --> 00:56:09.900
And that's what you
want, of course.

00:56:09.900 --> 00:56:11.740
You want to be able to
drive well at night.

00:56:11.740 --> 00:56:14.220
You want to be able to
drive well in the daytime.

00:56:14.220 --> 00:56:18.370
And by having this system,
you can look at predominantly

00:56:18.370 --> 00:56:21.800
at contrast
differences rather than

00:56:21.800 --> 00:56:23.560
absolute levels of contrast.

00:56:23.560 --> 00:56:25.250
So that's the arrangement here.

00:56:25.250 --> 00:56:27.180
And now what we
are going to do is

00:56:27.180 --> 00:56:33.297
to move on and talk about
the so-called after-effects

00:56:33.297 --> 00:56:33.880
of adaptation.

00:56:36.010 --> 00:56:38.980
So let me tell you how
this initially was done.

00:56:40.200 --> 00:56:45.120
People ask the question, what
happens if I fix something

00:56:45.120 --> 00:56:50.345
on your retina for
a period of time?

00:56:51.800 --> 00:56:54.840
If that previous set of
data that I've shown you

00:56:54.840 --> 00:56:57.260
is correct, if I present
something to the retina

00:56:57.260 --> 00:56:59.980
and leave it there, pretty
soon you won't see anything.

00:57:03.100 --> 00:57:05.280
A famous series
of experiments was

00:57:05.280 --> 00:57:07.660
done, by now many,
many years ago,

00:57:07.660 --> 00:57:11.100
in which they-- very
clever experiment--

00:57:11.100 --> 00:57:13.780
had subjects lie down.

00:57:13.780 --> 00:57:16.950
And they put a contact
lens in the eye.

00:57:16.950 --> 00:57:22.930
And in the contact lens, they
put a miniature projector on,

00:57:22.930 --> 00:57:26.940
which meant that when you
turn that projector light on,

00:57:26.940 --> 00:57:30.830
it went to a fixed position
on the retinal surface.

00:57:30.830 --> 00:57:32.510
Why was this necessary?

00:57:32.510 --> 00:57:35.300
Well, the reason it
happened is because it

00:57:35.300 --> 00:57:38.850
was discovered that
your eye actually

00:57:38.850 --> 00:57:41.130
is not really stable on purpose.

00:57:41.130 --> 00:57:43.020
Your eye ha a
so-called eye tremor.

00:57:44.100 --> 00:57:46.770
And of course, you move
your eyes all the time.

00:57:46.770 --> 00:57:51.000
So this procedure of
having a contact lens

00:57:51.000 --> 00:57:54.870
with a projector
attached to it kind of

00:57:54.870 --> 00:57:56.435
got rid of the eye tremor.

00:57:57.830 --> 00:58:04.710
So when they did
that, they found that,

00:58:04.710 --> 00:58:08.070
depending on the contrast, in
a matter of a minute or less,

00:58:08.070 --> 00:58:11.370
maybe even 30 seconds,
you would stop

00:58:11.370 --> 00:58:16.020
seeing what was
presented to the eye

00:58:16.020 --> 00:58:20.470
because you then
change the adaptation

00:58:20.470 --> 00:58:22.570
level in your photoreceptors.

00:58:23.710 --> 00:58:26.830
So then subsequently,
people had a clever idea.

00:58:26.830 --> 00:58:29.590
Said, we don't need to go
through this incredible trouble

00:58:29.590 --> 00:58:33.526
of having to have people with
contact lenses and a projector,

00:58:33.526 --> 00:58:35.150
and having them lie
down because that's

00:58:35.150 --> 00:58:36.500
the only way it would work.

00:58:36.500 --> 00:58:38.830
We can do this much more simply.

00:58:38.830 --> 00:58:42.820
And so to do that, I'm going
to have a demonstration here.

00:58:42.820 --> 00:58:44.990
What I would like
each of you to do

00:58:44.990 --> 00:58:48.930
is to-- you see it's a light
spot here and dark spot there.

00:58:48.930 --> 00:58:53.280
So I want you to fixate
here and count to about 30.

00:58:54.810 --> 00:58:56.980
And be very relaxed about it.

00:58:56.980 --> 00:58:57.990
This is a Gaussian.

00:58:57.990 --> 00:59:00.730
Therefore there's no sharp
edge and the eye tremor

00:59:00.730 --> 00:59:01.820
doesn't matter.

00:59:01.820 --> 00:59:04.270
Then after you counted
to 30, shift your gaze

00:59:04.270 --> 00:59:05.370
to the bottom one.

00:59:10.675 --> 00:59:12.180
The first thing
that happens if you

00:59:12.180 --> 00:59:14.340
keep looking at it,
the two on the top

00:59:14.340 --> 00:59:18.660
here disappear if you
fixate very tightly.

00:59:18.660 --> 00:59:21.600
And once they disappear,
then you can look down.

00:59:23.975 --> 00:59:25.100
Everybody see it disappear?

00:59:26.490 --> 00:59:27.030
Good.

00:59:27.030 --> 00:59:29.112
And what happened when
you looked at the bottom?

00:59:29.112 --> 00:59:30.028
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:59:31.000 --> 00:59:32.840
PROFESSOR: You got
a reversal, right?

00:59:32.840 --> 00:59:35.505
You got a dark spot here
and a light spot here.

00:59:35.505 --> 00:59:38.310
And you say oh my god,
what's going on here?

00:59:39.660 --> 00:59:42.440
So now let's do
another experiment.

00:59:42.440 --> 00:59:44.290
I want you to do this again.

00:59:44.290 --> 00:59:47.610
But what I want you to do is
to cover one eye up and then

00:59:47.610 --> 00:59:48.210
do it again.

00:59:48.210 --> 00:59:49.400
Count to 30.

00:59:49.400 --> 00:59:53.470
And after you did so, make
[INAUDIBLE] down the bottom,

00:59:53.470 --> 00:59:54.880
but switch your eye.

00:59:59.950 --> 01:00:04.790
And if you switch the eye,
cover the one that you looked at

01:00:04.790 --> 01:00:07.650
and uncover the one
that you didn't look at.

01:00:07.650 --> 01:00:10.450
And if you do that, you
won't get any effect.

01:00:10.450 --> 01:00:12.240
So what does that prove?

01:00:12.240 --> 01:00:14.690
That prove that this is
happening in the retina.

01:00:15.820 --> 01:00:17.170
Everybody agree?

01:00:18.470 --> 01:00:19.290
Very clear cut.

01:00:20.430 --> 01:00:22.970
So what's going on here?

01:00:22.970 --> 01:00:25.600
So let's diagram this.

01:00:25.600 --> 01:00:27.310
Here we have the situation.

01:00:27.310 --> 01:00:28.735
You turned on these two stimuli.

01:00:30.200 --> 01:00:34.180
And then when we turn it down,
initially their sensitivity

01:00:34.180 --> 01:00:36.350
of your photoreceptors
is pretty much the same

01:00:36.350 --> 01:00:38.260
because it was a
homogeneous background.

01:00:38.260 --> 01:00:41.650
Then after you looked at this
for awhile-- no, one more

01:00:41.650 --> 01:00:42.450
thing.

01:00:42.450 --> 01:00:44.900
In this case, the ON cells
fired, and in this case,

01:00:44.900 --> 01:00:48.770
the OFF cells fired, saying,
oh, dark spot, oh, light spot.

01:00:48.770 --> 01:00:52.030
Now, if you keep looking at
this for awhile, what happens

01:00:52.030 --> 01:00:53.550
is it begins to disappear.

01:00:53.550 --> 01:00:56.750
When it does, what happens
is you don't see anything

01:00:56.750 --> 01:01:01.330
and what happens also is that
the sensitivity here decreases

01:01:01.330 --> 01:01:04.530
for white light and [INAUDIBLE]
increases here for white light.

01:01:04.530 --> 01:01:08.470
So therefore, what happens
is once you adapted to this,

01:01:08.470 --> 01:01:14.720
there is no response
in the ganglion cells.

01:01:14.720 --> 01:01:17.450
Then for the third step.

01:01:17.450 --> 01:01:19.930
When you've made
yourself look down,

01:01:19.930 --> 01:01:21.950
there were homogeneous
background.

01:01:21.950 --> 01:01:24.990
But this region is less and
this region's more sensitive.

01:01:24.990 --> 01:01:29.790
And so therefore the
photons come into your eye

01:01:29.790 --> 01:01:33.010
from those two regions hit
more and less sensitive

01:01:33.010 --> 01:01:37.140
regions on the rental
surface, thereby activating

01:01:37.140 --> 01:01:40.600
the opposite cells-- here
activating the OFF cells,

01:01:40.600 --> 01:01:42.040
here activating the ON cells.

01:01:44.290 --> 01:01:47.864
Sorry-- right, yeah.

01:01:49.136 --> 01:01:50.740
We got a reversal.

01:01:50.740 --> 01:01:53.950
So that explains why
you see the after image.

01:01:55.620 --> 01:01:58.900
So now we're going to
continue and get back

01:01:58.900 --> 01:02:05.050
to the question of
the color circle,

01:02:05.050 --> 01:02:07.605
see what happens with
after images with color.

01:02:09.310 --> 01:02:16.170
So this color circle is
unbelievably powerful

01:02:16.170 --> 01:02:21.130
because it explains the after
images that you see with color.

01:02:21.130 --> 01:02:23.520
And I will come
back to this circle.

01:02:23.520 --> 01:02:26.400
But what I want
you to do now again

01:02:26.400 --> 01:02:32.200
is to fixate here, count
until, again, about 30,

01:02:32.200 --> 01:02:33.600
and then fixate on the bottom.

01:02:49.800 --> 01:02:53.640
So if you do that, I think
most of you should see,

01:02:53.640 --> 01:02:54.537
again, a reversal.

01:02:54.537 --> 01:02:55.870
Here you would see some reddish.

01:02:55.870 --> 01:02:57.510
Here you would see
something greenish.

01:02:57.510 --> 01:02:59.280
Does everybody see that?

01:02:59.280 --> 01:03:00.520
Do you see that too?

01:03:00.520 --> 01:03:01.020
Good.

01:03:02.220 --> 01:03:04.490
So you have a very
minor color deficit.

01:03:06.070 --> 01:03:08.250
So that's the case here.

01:03:08.250 --> 01:03:09.870
So now let me show
you another one.

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:14.790
And again, do the
same experiment.

01:03:26.160 --> 01:03:29.260
And what you see here at the
after images you get-- whoops.

01:03:29.260 --> 01:03:29.760
Sorry.

01:03:30.795 --> 01:03:31.420
Let me go back.

01:03:31.420 --> 01:03:35.950
The after images
you get here are not

01:03:35.950 --> 01:03:38.850
going to be the
complimentaries here.

01:03:38.850 --> 01:03:40.570
So what's going on?

01:03:40.570 --> 01:03:42.360
So let me explain it to you.

01:03:42.360 --> 01:03:43.755
Here again is a color circle.

01:03:45.200 --> 01:03:47.170
And here the prime axes.

01:03:47.170 --> 01:03:53.640
It turns out that if you
adapt to this level here,

01:03:53.640 --> 01:03:58.077
the rule of the color circle
says if you go across,

01:03:58.077 --> 01:03:59.910
this is the after image
you're going to see.

01:04:01.370 --> 01:04:04.590
And if you adapt to here,
this is the after image

01:04:04.590 --> 01:04:05.650
you're going to see.

01:04:05.650 --> 01:04:07.140
So let me draw that up.

01:04:07.140 --> 01:04:08.140
It looks like that.

01:04:10.230 --> 01:04:14.430
And that is true everywhere, as
long as you go across the axis.

01:04:14.430 --> 01:04:18.320
You could do this horizontally
or even diagonally,

01:04:18.320 --> 01:04:19.565
and you get this reversal.

01:04:20.720 --> 01:04:25.610
So it says that an after image
can be perfectly predicted

01:04:25.610 --> 01:04:27.530
by the rules of
the color circle.

01:04:27.530 --> 01:04:31.950
It's on the opposite
side of the image

01:04:31.950 --> 01:04:34.430
that you look at,
going across the center

01:04:34.430 --> 01:04:37.030
along the cardinal axis.

01:04:37.030 --> 01:04:41.240
But now if you do the diagonals,
which I showed you before,

01:04:41.240 --> 01:04:43.540
when it didn't match,
what we have here,

01:04:43.540 --> 01:04:45.120
you have this and this.

01:04:45.120 --> 01:04:46.810
Then the after image
is this and that.

01:04:46.810 --> 01:04:50.500
And so we don't have a
correspondence, of course,

01:04:50.500 --> 01:04:59.490
because you're not along the
axes that would predict this.

01:04:59.490 --> 01:05:01.680
This one gives you that
and this one give you that.

01:05:01.680 --> 01:05:04.380
So if I did this and
this to begin with,

01:05:04.380 --> 01:05:06.130
it would be the same
as that, but rotated.

01:05:08.090 --> 01:05:15.020
So that then clearly enables
us to use the color circle

01:05:15.020 --> 01:05:18.010
to predict not only some of the
basic effects of what colors

01:05:18.010 --> 01:05:20.400
we see, but also to tell
you exactly what kinds

01:05:20.400 --> 01:05:21.787
of after images you get.

01:05:21.787 --> 01:05:22.495
Quite remarkable.

01:05:23.960 --> 01:05:26.770
So now to drive
this home once more.

01:05:26.770 --> 01:05:29.330
This doesn't work too well
because the colors are crummy

01:05:29.330 --> 01:05:31.037
here, but we can try it.

01:05:31.037 --> 01:05:33.620
Everybody agree this is sort of
a more or less black and white

01:05:33.620 --> 01:05:35.770
display-- a little
bluish, unfortunately,

01:05:35.770 --> 01:05:38.035
here-- of a beautiful castle?

01:05:39.600 --> 01:05:41.590
See that fixation point here?

01:05:41.590 --> 01:05:44.840
What I want you to do
here is to fixate here,

01:05:44.840 --> 01:05:48.210
again, count to 30, and
then I'll switch back to it.

01:05:49.790 --> 01:05:52.150
And if this were
to work right, you

01:05:52.150 --> 01:05:55.840
would see the original black
and white image in color.

01:05:57.210 --> 01:05:58.345
Keep fixating.

01:05:58.345 --> 01:05:59.890
Count to 20 more.

01:05:59.890 --> 01:06:01.256
And then I'll switch back.

01:06:06.940 --> 01:06:08.527
Did you see the colors?

01:06:08.527 --> 01:06:09.690
Yeah.

01:06:09.690 --> 01:06:13.100
So this is a very
clever demo I found.

01:06:13.100 --> 01:06:15.140
I'm afraid I don't
remember the person's name

01:06:15.140 --> 01:06:17.350
who came up with this one.

01:06:17.350 --> 01:06:22.230
But the essence of it is, again,
that indeed what is happening

01:06:22.230 --> 01:06:28.115
is that you're creating an
after effect due to adaptation

01:06:28.115 --> 01:06:28.770
in the retina.

01:06:31.892 --> 01:06:33.350
And when you do
this very cleverly,

01:06:33.350 --> 01:06:37.430
like this particular
castle picture,

01:06:37.430 --> 01:06:40.350
you can actually create
an artificial impression

01:06:40.350 --> 01:06:43.420
of colors which are in
consonance with what

01:06:43.420 --> 01:06:46.170
the real colors would look like
in a black and white picture.

01:06:47.220 --> 01:06:50.300
So that then is
the essence of what

01:06:50.300 --> 01:06:52.460
I wanted to cover
about adaptation.

01:06:52.460 --> 01:06:56.120
And we can now
come and summarize

01:06:56.120 --> 01:06:58.890
what I had covered today.

01:07:02.850 --> 01:07:04.885
So first of all, I
told you that there

01:07:04.885 --> 01:07:08.450
are three qualities of
color-- hue, brightness,

01:07:08.450 --> 01:07:09.100
and saturation.

01:07:10.300 --> 01:07:13.230
And just to go back--
hang on for a minute.

01:07:13.230 --> 01:07:18.230
I want to go back once
more to make this clear,

01:07:18.230 --> 01:07:19.570
which I forgot to mention.

01:07:19.570 --> 01:07:22.820
If you go around the
circle, you change hue.

01:07:25.930 --> 01:07:30.240
And if you go from the
periphery to the center,

01:07:30.240 --> 01:07:31.170
you change saturation.

01:07:34.410 --> 01:07:39.040
And the center here, if this
color circle were 100% correct,

01:07:39.040 --> 01:07:40.805
this would be a white area.

01:07:47.270 --> 01:07:49.660
Now, the basic rules
of color vision

01:07:49.660 --> 01:07:53.960
are explained by the color
circle, as we have amply seen.

01:07:53.960 --> 01:07:57.200
There's something probably--
I have a color circle

01:07:57.200 --> 01:08:01.162
up on my wall in my office
because I'm always fascinated

01:08:01.162 --> 01:08:03.245
by this, even though I've
been doing it for years.

01:08:05.130 --> 01:08:09.360
So the three photoreceptors
we talked about in humans

01:08:09.360 --> 01:08:11.890
and in primates, the red,
green, and blue, which

01:08:11.890 --> 01:08:13.640
shouldn't be called that.

01:08:13.640 --> 01:08:16.130
People get mad when you do
that, even though that's the way

01:08:16.130 --> 01:08:17.010
I call it.

01:08:17.010 --> 01:08:18.840
But people want to call
them short, medium,

01:08:18.840 --> 01:08:20.800
and long-wavelength cones.

01:08:21.910 --> 01:08:25.010
They are broadly tuned,
as I had shown you

01:08:25.010 --> 01:08:26.240
in those spectrograms.

01:08:27.939 --> 01:08:30.910
The color-opponent midget
retinal ganglion cells

01:08:30.910 --> 01:08:34.230
form two cardinal axes, the
red/green and the blue/yellow.

01:08:38.250 --> 01:08:41.189
And those, if you
remember I told you

01:08:41.189 --> 01:08:43.180
at the level of the
retinal ganglion cells

01:08:43.180 --> 01:08:48.330
and at the level of the
lateral geniculate nucleus,

01:08:48.330 --> 01:08:51.109
fall into these two
major categories.

01:08:51.109 --> 01:08:53.029
We won't have any
under diagonals.

01:08:53.029 --> 01:08:56.140
So for us to be properly
able to see diagonals,

01:08:56.140 --> 01:08:58.390
that's done somewhere
in the cortex.

01:08:58.390 --> 01:09:00.069
It's not done at the
level of the retina

01:09:00.069 --> 01:09:01.485
or the lateral
geniculate nucleus.

01:09:03.450 --> 01:09:05.979
Now, I also pointed out
to you several times

01:09:05.979 --> 01:09:08.255
already that the midget
system's essential for color

01:09:08.255 --> 01:09:08.880
discrimination.

01:09:10.439 --> 01:09:15.210
And the parasol cells can see
stimuli even at isoluminance.

01:09:17.010 --> 01:09:19.620
They just cannot say
what the color is.

01:09:19.620 --> 01:09:23.100
They don't, quotes,
"perceive" different colors.

01:09:23.100 --> 01:09:26.729
But they can see
any kind of change

01:09:26.729 --> 01:09:28.609
that occurs in the
environment, even when it

01:09:28.609 --> 01:09:29.567
occurs at isoluminance.

01:09:34.550 --> 01:09:37.229
Color is processed in
many cortical areas,

01:09:37.229 --> 01:09:41.899
lesions to any single
extrastriate area

01:09:41.899 --> 01:09:44.090
fails to eliminate
the processing

01:09:44.090 --> 01:09:45.630
of chrominance information.

01:09:45.630 --> 01:09:49.390
It can reduce it, but
it doesn't block it out.

01:09:49.390 --> 01:09:50.880
That's true for many things.

01:09:53.410 --> 01:09:56.510
So the cortical areas
are very, very complex.

01:09:57.540 --> 01:10:01.950
And they do interactive analysis
for many different attributes,

01:10:01.950 --> 01:10:03.070
including color.

01:10:05.480 --> 01:10:10.240
However, I can add here that
does not apply to area MT

01:10:10.240 --> 01:10:13.080
because MT does not
seem to be specializing

01:10:13.080 --> 01:10:16.786
in color because lesions there,
you [INAUDIBLE] any deficit.

01:10:16.786 --> 01:10:18.410
But there's several
other visual areas.

01:10:18.410 --> 01:10:22.040
We went through that, V3, and
[INAUDIBLE] cortex, and so on.

01:10:23.066 --> 01:10:28.070
These areas contribute to
the processing of color.

01:10:28.070 --> 01:10:30.300
Now, the perception
of isoluminance

01:10:30.300 --> 01:10:33.680
is categorized for all
categories of vision.

01:10:33.680 --> 01:10:35.760
It's not selected
to only those that

01:10:35.760 --> 01:10:39.940
are processed by the midget
or the parasol systems.

01:10:39.940 --> 01:10:42.330
All aspects of vision--
and the three I

01:10:42.330 --> 01:10:46.916
showed you was,
stereopsis, motion,

01:10:46.916 --> 01:10:49.480
and what was the third one?

01:10:49.480 --> 01:10:50.460
AUDIENCE: Texture.

01:10:50.460 --> 01:10:51.700
PROFESSOR: Texture, right.

01:10:51.700 --> 01:10:57.140
So all three of
those are compromised

01:10:57.140 --> 01:11:00.100
when stimuli are
presented at isoluminance.

01:11:01.400 --> 01:11:03.980
The most significant aspect
of luminance adaptation

01:11:03.980 --> 01:11:06.210
occurs in the photoreceptors.

01:11:06.210 --> 01:11:11.110
And it's explainable by the
relative number at any given

01:11:11.110 --> 01:11:16.930
level of adaptation of bleached
and unbleached photoreceptor

01:11:16.930 --> 01:11:20.570
molecules, as in the
case of rhodopsin.

01:11:20.570 --> 01:11:24.920
Lastly, after images are
a product of photoreceptor

01:11:24.920 --> 01:11:30.360
adaptation and their subsequent
response to the incoming light.

01:11:31.530 --> 01:11:36.190
So that then is the essence of
what you wanted to cover today.

01:11:36.190 --> 01:11:39.740
And I hope you did
find this interesting,

01:11:39.740 --> 01:11:41.240
because certainly
our ability to see

01:11:41.240 --> 01:11:43.140
color is quite a
remarkable thing.

01:11:43.140 --> 01:11:47.930
It's amazing to get a sense
of how the nervous system does

01:11:47.930 --> 01:11:50.260
that, even though
at this stage, we

01:11:50.260 --> 01:11:53.210
are still at a fairly
early level of having

01:11:53.210 --> 01:11:54.710
gained full understanding of it.

01:11:59.240 --> 01:12:02.450
Now the next time,
we are going to move

01:12:02.450 --> 01:12:05.860
on to another fascinating topic,
at least for me fascinating,

01:12:05.860 --> 01:12:09.180
which is depth perception,
which I had mentioned

01:12:09.180 --> 01:12:15.190
before is a remarkable
achievement because images fall

01:12:15.190 --> 01:12:17.400
on a two-dimensional
retinal surface.

01:12:17.400 --> 01:12:19.140
And from that, the
third dimension

01:12:19.140 --> 01:12:20.840
has to be reconstructed.

01:12:20.840 --> 01:12:24.410
And how that is done, we are
going to discuss the next time.

